# Scale Up Web Infrastructure

## For every additional element, why you are adding it

- Additional server:
  I added one more server to separate infrastructure components and reduce resource competition between the web server, application server, and database.

- Second load balancer:
  I added a second HAProxy load balancer and configured it as a cluster with the first load balancer to remove the load balancer as a Single Point of Failure.

- Load balancer cluster:
  The two load balancers work together to improve availability. If one load balancer fails, the other can continue routing traffic to the servers.

- Separate web server:
  I separated the web server into its own server so Nginx can focus on handling HTTP/HTTPS requests and serving static content.

- Separate application server:
  I separated the application server into its own server so it can focus on running the application logic and code base.

- Separate database server:
  I separated the database into its own server so MySQL can use dedicated resources for storing, reading, and writing data.

## Application server vs Web server

A web server, such as Nginx, handles incoming HTTP/HTTPS requests, serves static files, and forwards dynamic requests to the application server.

An application server runs the application code and business logic. It processes dynamic requests and communicates with the database when data is needed.

## Summary

This infrastructure improves scalability, availability, and performance by separating the main components into different servers and adding a second load balancer configured as a cluster.